Title: The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice

reviewText: This movie is actually the third installment in a series, and Flynn, the main character, is a librarian who goes on missions collecting rare and historic relics for the Metropolitan Library of New York. The library has a secret amazing basement filled with treasures from all over the world, and getting a glimpse of its wonders really adds to the fun of the show.Flynn's character works well because he knows so much and adds pieces to the story through his random factual interludes and references. The Librarian's vast knowledge and love of information really brings the whole story together. He kind of teaches you, and the action and suspense are almost like extras. I doubt that all of the things he says are true, but they sure captured my attention and made me want to know more.I liked the idea of the Judas Chalice having a vampiric history. Definitely a good twist in the plot. I am not usually into the vampire thing, but it was fun and suspenseful and not the boring, same-old stuff we're used to when it comes to those creatures of the night. I also liked the little love story between Flynn and Simone. It had its own little twist as well.Bob Newhart is loveable as kooky Judson, and Jane Curtin is also good in her nerdy role. Noah Wyle really surprised me, though. He's funny and nerdy-hot and an action hero all at once. It's Indiana Jones-esque. I think Wyle makes the perfect Librarian. I definitely want to see the rest of the series now. I hope they make many more. Definitely recommended.Keep in mind this is a made for TV series.
summary: Don't judge a book by its cover...

reviewText: Firstly, although lower budget than the Indianna Jones films of the same type of storyboard it is not chintzy or distracting from the movie.The hero is interesting and entertaining in what appears to be the last of the trilogy, as he portrays life's effects upon us all.He needs a vacation from saving the world after his girlfriends disasterous telephone timing - something we've probably all done without being privelaged to be aware on the day.Vacation obtained after the temper tantrum many of us might wish we could throw at work the poor man finds there is actually no way he can escape either work or love, even while on vacation.One could say that workwise his cup runneth over while the his love life returned with something of a bite, working its way towards poingnancy.The writers did a good job with this, there's everything from voodoo to vampires woven into the storyline, but well woven. The special effects are above average for this type of film, the acting varies from deadpan to hilarious but is consistently of better than average quality - and New Orleans is always an excellent backdrop.I've now purchased the other two in the series - no, they're not Indiana Jones but for some they're possibly even more enjoyable, for the rest of us they're simply excellent entertainment and great for a quiet evening when a more action orientated family film is desirable.
summary: Indiana Jones type quality entertainment on a budget

Title: The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice

reviewText: With today's vampire-mania, this third installation in the Librarian saga is perfectly positioned for success.  Noah Wyle (as Flynn Carson) and company (Bob Newhart as Judson and Jane Curtin as Charlene) are on the track, this time, of, not the Holy Grail, but its opposite number, the Judas Chalice, which, as Flynn learns, was instrumental in the creation of the very first vampire, its original owner Judas Iscariot--and has the power to create more of them with no nonsense about biting necks.  But Flynn is approaching burnout after battling evil in some 35 forms and losing several girlfriends to his hectic and unpredictable lifestyle.  When he finally resigns himself to the job, he finds that he isn't the only one in search of the Chalice: a former KGB officer (Dikran Tulaine), assisted by a handicapped college professor (Bruce Davison) who turns out to be a lot more than he seems, wants it to help him restore Russia to her former glory by assembling an undead and unkillable army of vamps.  Deciphering a string of clues in post-Katrina New Orleans and teaming up with a seductive Creole chanteuse (Stana Katic) who also isn't telling everything she knows, Flynn finds himself once again up to his ears in danger and learning some things about himself and the Library (particularly Judson, who may well be just as immortal as any bloodsucker not alive) that he never suspected before.  Jonathan Frakes of "Star Trek: The Next Generation" directs with a fine hand for pacing and the effects, as always, are top-notch.  Those who, like myself, enjoyed the two previous chapters in this franchise must definitely not miss this one.

reviewText: A friend of mine recommended this TV movie as the best of the series of 3 about "The Librarian," a fantasy adventure that makes me almost wish such magical wonders did really lurk behind the card catalog files and closed doors at the New York Public Library!  Being a big fan of "Castle" star Stana Katic also made this film a must-see for me, and her remarkably different character in this (and her surprising good singing voice in a sultry and haunting ballad) add even more to my appreciation.  Some people compare this to the Indiana Jones movies or the H. Rider Haggard movies, but this is really different enough in its own quirky way to stand alone on its own merits.  With good comedic touches by veterans Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin that add to the fun but never overwhelm, spoofs without being campy and is scary enough to make you worry about the main characters.  I would love to see more like this one!
summary: A delightful film that's better than average TV movies.

reviewText: This movie is either a low budget production meant to make money or a made-for-TV movie's DVD release meant to make more money. In either case we have sophomoric acting & a disjointed script with attempts at light humor. Or was it satire? No matter, hard to tell because it failed at both. Green screen generated backdrops were obviously low budget as shown by a total of two or three CG effects - blurry fast people and dying sparkly, already dead people. Both effects seen in countless other fantasy movies the past 8 years. The movie is also one improbable event after another including a librarian whose brain contains a data base the size of the Library of Congress. On the positive side: a pretty good ending where for the first time there was some emotive acting.
Title: The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice

reviewText: - An outraged Flynn Carsen (on having his tuxedo shirt ripped during a sword duel): "This is rented!"- His evil (yet urbane) opponent: "Of course it is."It's always a guilty pleasure catching up with the Librarian, whose job is to guard history's secret relics and treasures, some of these magical in nature and all stowed away in the hidden chambers of the Metropolitan Library of New York. Flynn Carsen is sort of like a modern-day Indiana Jones, except that he's awkward and plenty nerdy. But Flynn does keep his wits about him, and, after years of holding down the Librarian gig, he now boasts experience and smidgens of confidence. This current Librarian may fumble about some, but it's always fun seeing how he'll get out of whatever scrape.The more things change... The movie opens with Flynn at a posh event applying the finishing touches to his tuxedo. He then navigates down a stairway,  sips champagne, and then does a spit take with the champagne. Which goes to show that, even after all this time, Flynn Carsen is still refreshingly hapless. But, after this latest escapade, which climaxes in a sword fight, Flynn Carsen is officially burnt out (his girlfriend dumping him has something to do with it). Back at the library, by virtue of sheer grousing, he gets himself some time off and ends up flying to New Orleans, all gigged out in bow tie and panama hat. So, as they say in the Big Easy, laissez les bon temps roullez.Or not. The holiday rapidly turns into a desperate relic hunt, with Flynn taking on ex-KGB agents, voodoo magic, and the undead. Along the way, he partners up with a mysterious chanteuse to rescue a kidnapped scientist. The relic in question is the rumored Judas Chalice, of which origin dates back to Judas Iscariot and his 30 pieces of silver. The chalice reeks of malice but holds the brew that is true - that is, if you're a vampire in need of resurrecting. And, since those ex-KGB agents have unearthed the coffin of Vlad Dracul, you can see where this is going.What I like best about TNT's Librarian series is that it's not at all pretentious. It wallows in its unabashed cheesiness and farce, even as it hunkers down with a pretty good adventure story. THE LIBRARIAN: CURSE OF THE JUDAS CHALICE is the third in the series, and it doesn't disappoint its fans. Hokey fun, mythical artifacts, indecipherable manuscripts, supernatural villains, and a likable, nebbish, talky hero (even the bad guys complain of his always talking in paragraphs). By now, Noah Wyle's got his part down cold. The neat thing about his character is that he can do something heroic but, then, subsequently have the rug pulled out from under him. And, when this happens, he's so damn good-natured about it.Flynn has had a hard time keeping his lady loves. First Nicole (Sonya Walger), then Emily Davenport (Gabrielle Anwar). This time out, Wyle's romantic interest is exotic Stana Katic, who plays bluesy singer Simone Renoir with femme fatale nuances. Maybe she's a keeper. Or not. Meanwhile, Jane Curtin and Bob Newhart (at his stammering best) are again solidly on board as the museum directors.I never thought I'd ever say this, but I had a better time with THE LIBRARIAN: CURSE OF THE JUDAS CHALICE than with that last Indiana Jones flick. This movie, like its predecessors (The Librarian - Quest for the Spear&The Librarian  - Return to King Solomon's Mines) are tongue-in-cheek throwbacks to those high adventure pictures churned out back in the 1930s, '40s and '50s. I don't think I'm reaching that much when I say that even the score here is rousing enough that it actually reminded me of those Errol Flynn swashbucklers. But, of course, Flynn Carsen is no Errol Flynn. Errol doesn't know the Dewey Decimal System.
summary: Treasure hunts, exotic beauties, saving the world - it's good to be the Librarian

reviewText: The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice (2008-tvm).Running Time: One hour, 30 mins.Directed by Jonathan Frakes. Written by Marco Schnabel, David N. Titcher.Third tv-movie and the last in the series until the tv series in 2014.Returning: Noah Wyle, Bob Newhart, Jane Curtin.Flynn (Noah Wyle) is at the London Glen Auction dressed like James Bond. Charlene (Jane Curtin) whom is watching the bids on internet tells Flynn by cell phone to be careful with his bidding and what ever he does, don't let Ivan (Jason Douglas) walk away with the green Dynasty vase. Just then, Kate (Beth Burvant) calls Flynn. She has been stood up by Flynn and is an emotional wreck. He is late. While he is talking to Kate, the bid for the vase increases ever so high. Finally Flynn has the last bid of f1,000,000. Sold to Flynn. Charlene faints to the floor. Upon paying the bid, Flynn breaks the vase and finds the Philosopher's Stone inside. Ivan wants the stone and attempts to kill Flynn for it. How will Flynn get out of this?Well, back at the Metropolitan Public Library, Flynn gets a talking to from Charlene. The amount is way to high to pay, but then is shown another another secret large part of the library. it contains Noah's Ark and the Fountain of Youth.  Flynn has a breakdown over the loss of his new girlfriend and losing other girlfriends because of this job. So Judson (Bob Newhart) and Charlene recommend vacation time.After getting drunk at a wine-tasting event, Charlene visits Flynn and gives him some traveling brochures. Flynn decies to take a trip to New Orleans. He meets Simone Renoir (Stana Katic), a singer at a club. This leads to an adventure of the Judas Chalice.Also in the cast: Bruce Davison, Dikran Tulaine, Joe Knezevich, Armando Leduc, Antonio Echeverria, Joe Ross, Jonathan Frakes.Filmed in Baton Rouge, Harahan, New Orleans, Louisiana.Hmm. I wonder where they got the idea for the Philosopher's Stone?Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone [Blu-ray] (2001).Language in English. Subtitles in Spanish.Special Features: Deleted Scenes. Visual Effects Deconstruction Sequences. A Look Behind the Monastery Scene.The Librarian - Quest for the Spear(2004-tvm).The Librarian  - Return to King Solomon's Mines(2006-tvm).The Librarian: Curse of the Judas Chalice (2008-tvm).Update: The Librarian tv series will be broadcast on TNT this Autumn 2014, 10 episodes.
summary: Flynn Carsen finds an adventure in New Orleans.

reviewText: The third entry in the Librarian franchise in many ways lives up to the standards set by the first two. There is an interesting and exciting story with great action, great characterization, and wonderful touches of humor. The romantic element is also present. Stana Katic absolutely burns out the pixels on the widescreen. She was perfectly cast. Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin are great supporting characters.But in a number of respects this was a disappointment. First, the introduction of fantasy creatures (vampires) takes the series in an undesirable direction. I understand that vampires have been all the rage for the last few years but I think the move to horror elements is a mistake. I had similar misgivings about aliens being introduced into the Indiana Jones series - it just doesn't feel right. I think the ghosts seen in Return to King Solomon's Mines is about as far in the direction of fantasy creatures as this series should go.Second, this film doesn't involve the same amount of globetrotting as the first two. All the action is in New Orleans. There is an opening scene in London but it probably wasn't filmed there. Each succeeding film in this series seems to do less and less location shooting. Maybe the budgets are too tight?Additionally, the extras were fairly lame. The deleted scenes are more properly described as deleted lines.But maybe that's just me. Despite the above, I enjoyed the film and look forward to future entries in the series. Recommended for fans of fantasy adventure.
summary: Too much of a departure for my tastes

reviewText: If you haven't bought the other two Librarian movies, be sure to add them to the cart and watch them in order.I bought them looking for something a little different, with action, that could be seen by my then 10 year old son.  I like Noah Wyle so I thought I'd give it a shot.  I thought they would be a kind of watered down Indiana Jones.  Boy, was I wrong.  They stand alone in the terrific entertainment department.Although not the biggest fan of Bob Newhart and Jane Curtin, I have to admit they did a fantastic job.  They've also brought in good actors that you don't see a lot of these days, like Gabrielle Anway, Robert Foxworth, Kyle MacLachlan, and Bruce Davidson.  No, it's not realistic, although they contain a lot of interesting historical information and references.  It's pure escapism and lots of fun.My son loves all three, although the third is his favorite.  There really isn't anything a kid can't see.We're both hoping that there will be more of these -- and soon!

reviewText: You wouldn't think Noah Wylie could carry a comedy-adventure series, but you'd be wrong, because he has. Not only that, the series manages to be fun and exciting, without gratuitous violence, sex, or swearing. The casting is excellent, with Bob Newhart and Jane Curtain in wonderfully understated roles, and the plots are interesting. Yes, the movies are low budget, but so what? Exercise your imagination! Remember Buckaroo Banzai? Now there was a low budget adventure film! As far as the third Librarian episode is concerned, the story may not be quite as strong as the first, but the characterization of the main characters is gradually deepening, and I think over time many more people will realize how strong this series is becoming. The third film is obviously setting up a fourth, and my intuition says that may be the last, but I hope not -- keep them coming! The bottom line here is that all three Librarian movies are wonderful escapist family entertainment. That's to be treasured these days.

reviewText: The only thing wrong with this movie is that there are no more in this series.  I love all "The Librarian" movies and I wish they would do more of them.  In this the librarian once more has to retrieve a legendary object and return it to the library. In the course of his quest he meets a real vampire and Vlad the Impaler himself! (If you don't know, Vlad was the insperation for Dracula! In fact he was called Dracula.) Once again he has to overcome any number of difficulties to win the object he's after.  Enjoy!

reviewText: This is the third of the "Librarian" TV movies with Noah Wyle and I think they keep improving each time out.  With all the vampire movies and books out there right now, it must have seemed only natural to pit Flynn against the undead and it did not disappoint! Action, humor and mystery in good combination. Bob Newhart and Jane Curtain were excellent as always and Excaliber had a very nice scene. That sword has definitely become a character in itself! The only downer is that I kept hearing that this was the final one and I'm really hoping that either I heard wrong or they change their mind! Great production values and good FX but these movies are definitely story and character-driven.  Make more please!!
summary: Just when you thought there wasn't anything good on TV

reviewText: I'm from New Orleans so I always get a kick out of movies and tv shows that mangle my city. You have to laugh, it's Hollywood. You watch a movie to take yourself out of reality, this does that. It campy fun, until it breaks your heart near the end.

reviewText: The movie was OK, but a sexy good vampire vs. the bad vampires, really?  Even in a fantasy vehicle like this that seems a bit out there.  Newhart and Wiley are funny together in New Orleans, one of the better moments of the film in my opinion.A caution for parents of younger family members who may want to watch this because of Stana Katic.  It is about vampires with accompanying violence. Another cautionary note for parents; they always had Stana's chest partially exposed either with low cut or unbuttoned tops even in this made for TV movie. Her dress in this movie was so tight you could see her reach down and pull it up just to be able to run in the action scenes.  I couldn't help but wonder how many takes it took in those scenes to get one where her dress actually stayed up and covered her that they could show.I viewed this only to see Stana in an early venture that I was able to watch.  She definitely can sing which is another amazing GOD given talent she has been blessed with.  The character role allowed her to show some skills especially in the tender close up scenes.  I especially enjoyed her final scene, that is the Stana we all became enamored with in Castle.Stana is a beautiful young lady, I like her acting very much, her talent is abundant and is a real throw back to the actresses of the 40's and early 50's who projected the emotions and feelings with a pose of posture a facial expression or a line said in a particular manner.  She can do the same (like she did in the first season of Castle), but today's Hollywood wants the female leads to swear like porn stars, speak with regular vulgarity, and expose body parts to the world.  No young lady should be made to do that just to work.  Stana is way to talented to have to do that, but it doesn't seem to matter to those in charge that her younger fans especially the young girls who idolize her watch and listen to what she says, what she does, and what she wears.  They don't care about them.I pray that Stana or someone close to her will realize very soon how talented she really is and stop all this other nonsense and provide scripts and vehicles for her to really stretch and use the talent she has been blessed with.  Stana is so much better than what she has had to work in thus far in her film career.I look forward to the time when I can view a movie with Stana in the female lead and enjoy the film and her character where I won't feel like I need a shower after sitting through it because of all the filth the movie industry throws at the viewing public today.preacherman
summary: Ok for a made for TV movie

reviewText: While like with the other two Librarian movies this at most ranks as a B-movie not bad but nothing really spectacular either which is pretty much expected.  Like with the other movie I got National Treasure this one was just to whit my anticipation for the Uncharted 3 game coming out November 1st and while the character of Flynn Carson is no Nathan Drake the character and storyline for the most part will keep you entertained enough as to not care to much about that.  The story of the movie is pretty much like the last two, you have Flynn off trying to claim mystical artifacts for the mysterious group that holds all mystical artifacts from Excalibur to the Shroud of Turin in a vast secured building commonly known as the Library.  While we won't get the Indiana Jones epic kind of action the is enough here to keep it from being boring and for the most part the cast seem to be enjoying themselves as they play their character roles.  So if you're looking for a treasure hunting action movie until the next Indiana Jones movie or the Uncharted 3 comes out then here's a very good one to check out and at a very reasonable price as well...
summary: Another Guilty Pleasure For Us With a Renewed Interest And Treasure Hunters
